he shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Nesle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["South German and Swiss German:","variant of   Nestel  .","from a diminutive of   Nast  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nestel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Wolfram.  Jewish Aron, Hyman.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational name for a ribbon and cord maker, from Middle High German <i>nestel</i> ‘(shoe)lace, drawstring, cord’."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle de Nesle was born about 1175, in Nesle, Somme, Picardie, France, her father, Jean de Nesle, was 26 and her mother, Elizabeth de Lambersart, was 22. She married Enguerrand II de Coucy. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"environ 1175–":"umbes 1175–Surnud","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1179–1229":"1179–1229","1182–1226":"1182–1226","1155–1224":"1155–1224","1196–1257":"1196–1257","1202–1263":"1202–1263","1150–1197":"1150–1197","environ 1175":"umbes 1175","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1263":"1263","1196":"1196","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1226":"1226","1202":"1202","1257":"1257","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1155":"1155","1229":"1229","Boves, Somme, Picardie, France":"Boves, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Laon, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Nesle, Somme, Picardy, France":"Nesle, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1175–":"noin 1175–Kuollut","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1179–1229":"1179–1229","1182–1226":"1182–1226","1155–1224":"1155–1224","1196–1257":"1196–1257","1202–1263":"1202–1263","1150–